USCIS data show that TPS applications are rarely denied (only 4,104 applications denied so far in FY 2023, and 122,712 approved), so this latest designation seems likely to increase it to over 1 million.

Although the duration of the TPS designation is 18 months, it is nearly impossible to cancel a TPS designation. Recall that the Trump Administration attempted to terminate TPS for Haiti, Sudan, El Salvador, Honduras, Nepal, and Nicaragua in 2017 and 2018. The terminations were effectively tied up in litigation until the Biden Administration redesignated those countries and ended the litigation. Effectively this means that the Venezuelan migrants who illegally entered in the United States so far during the Biden Administration will not be removed. And it only further incentivizes illegal migration, since others will expect yet another Venezuelan TPS redesignation to cover them in the future. But, of course, the protection is only temporary, so this sets up another DACA-like class of aliens who could, in theory, lose their status in a future Republican Administration.

On this day in 1871, the Texas legislature directed the governor to appoint a superintendent with a four-year term to administer the Texas Bureau of Immigration, with "the purpose of promoting and protecting immigration" into the state. The superintendent was empowered to use tax revenues to write material describing Texas as a destination for the immigrant and to appoint paid agents and volunteer lecturers to travel to southern and northern states as well as to Europe, to encourage potential immigrants to seek land in Texas. Gustav Loeffler served as the first superintendent until 1874, when Governor Richard Coke appointed Jerome Bonaparte Robertson to that position. Fiscal retrenchment incorporated in the Constitution of 1876 brought an end to the bureau, as the constitution included a specific prohibition against using state funds "for any purpose of bringing immigrants to the State."
